Governorship candidate of the African Democratic Congress (ADC) in Ekiti State, Wole Oluyede, has admonished voters to shun vote selling and moneybags in the June 18 election to avoid installing a bad government. Oluyede, who lamented that vote buying and selling has destroyed the country’s democratic fabrics, called on the people to cast their votes for candidates based on competence and credibility. He stressed the need for the electorate to scrutinise the competence, profile and antecedent of the candidates before making choice of whom to vote for.   Firms, businesses await CBN’s decision on rates     Ekiti needs continuity, says Fayemi     Gunmen set police station, vehicles ablaze in Anambra   The candidate, who spoke through the Director-General of his campaign organisaiton, also tasked the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) and security agencies to checkmate vote buying to protect the sanctity and integrity of the ballots. Oluyede described himself as the most qualified to govern Ekiti in terms of ‘exposure, competence, experience and professional accomplishments for the task of bringing the required dividends of democracy to the people’. According to him, his mission is to ‘rejuvenate Ekiti’s economy and tutor fresh blood in the rudiments of politics and governance to bring a paradigm shift in ways people are governed’.